The Digital Literacy Programme has brought immense benefits to local communities countrywide, Public Service and Youth PS Lillian Omolo said yesterday.The PS said the programme has hastened provision of electricity to schools and communities, created jobs at ICT support centres and increased ICT skills among teachers and communities. She spoke at Jaribu Primary School in Garissa during inspection of tablets distribution.Omolo said the programme had created business opportunities for digital content developers. She asked local communities to ensure the devices are secure. After all, it is our future at stake. As government, we are convinced that DLP puts the country on the right track to be a global ICT player, she said.The Digital Literacy Programme is a flagship project for the government and part of the Vision 2030 s Social Pillar aimed at making Kenya a knowledge-based economy.